Thanks — this is a good starting point. A few high-level points first, then concrete suggestions and a sample implementation.

High-level feedback
- Your class is currently a thin wrapper around a JavaScript array. That is perfectly fine for many use-cases — JS arrays are dynamic and highly optimized in modern engines. Using an array gives you O(1) random access (get) and amortized O(1) push, but splice/remove from arbitrary index is O(n).
- A "true" linked list is a structure of nodes with pointers (next / prev). It has different trade-offs: O(1) insertion/removal at known node (or at head/tail if you maintain pointers), but O(n) indexed access (get by index).
- Decide which behavior you want. If you want the semantics and complexity of a linked list, implement nodes and pointers. If you intentionally want an array-backed list for simplicity (and usually better real-world performance in JS), document that.

Other issues / improvements in your code
- No bounds checking in remove/get; calling remove with an invalid index will behave unexpectedly.
- remove doesn't return the removed item; that can be useful.
- No size property or length tracking, no iteration helper methods, no clear/insert methods.
- Naming: methods like push/pop/shift/unshift are more conventional (but "add" is OK if intentional).

If you want a proper singly linked list, here is a concise implementation with common operations, O(1) push (tail), O(1) shift (head), O(n) get/remove by index, length tracking, and iteration support:

```javascript
class LinkedList {
  constructor() {
    this.head = null;
    this.tail = null;
    this.length = 0;
  }

  // internal node class
  static Node(value) {
    return { value, next: null };
  }

  // Add to the end (push)
  add(value) {
    const node = LinkedList.Node(value);
    if (!this.head) {
      this.head = node;
      this.tail = node;
    } else {
      this.tail.next = node;
      this.tail = node;
    }
    this.length++;
    return this; // allow chaining
  }

  // Get value by index (0-based)
  get(index) {
    if (index < 0 || index >= this.length) return undefined;
    let cur = this.head;
    for (let i = 0; i < index; i++) cur = cur.next;
    return cur.value;
  }

  // Remove and return item at index (0-based)
  remove(index) {
    if (index < 0 || index >= this.length) return undefined;

    let removed;
    if (index === 0) {
      removed = this.head;
      this.head = this.head.next;
      if (this.length === 1) this.tail = null;
    } else {
      let prev = this.head;
      for (let i = 0; i < index - 1; i++) prev = prev.next;
      removed = prev.next;
      prev.next = removed.next;
      if (removed === this.tail) this.tail = prev;
    }
    this.length--;
    return removed.value;
  }

  // Insert at index (0-based)
  insert(index, value) {
    if (index < 0 || index > this.length) throw new RangeError('Index out of bounds');
    if (index === 0) {
      const node = LinkedList.Node(value);
      node.next = this.head;
      this.head = node;
      if (this.length === 0) this.tail = node;
      this.length++;
      return this;
    }
    if (index === this.length) return this.add(value);

    let prev = this.head;
    for (let i = 0; i < index - 1; i++) prev = prev.next;
    const node = LinkedList.Node(value);
    node.next = prev.next;
    prev.next = node;
    this.length++;
    return this;
  }

  // Convert to array
  toArray() {
    const arr = [];
    let cur = this.head;
    while (cur) {
      arr.push(cur.value);
      cur = cur.next;
    }
    return arr;
  }

  // Allow for...of iteration
  *[Symbol.iterator]() {
    let cur = this.head;
    while (cur) {
      yield cur.value;
      cur = cur.next;
    }
  }

  isEmpty() {
    return this.length === 0;
  }

  clear() {
    this.head = this.tail = null;
    this.length = 0;
  }
}
```

Complexity summary (for the above singly-linked list)
- add (push): O(1)
- get by index: O(n)
- remove by index: O(n) (O(1) for head)
- insert at arbitrary index: O(n) (O(1) for head/tail with helpers)

When to prefer array vs linked list in JS
- Use arrays for random access, frequent iteration, and when you rely on built-in array methods. Arrays are often faster in practice because of engine optimizations.
- Use a linked list when you need many O(1) insertions/removals at the head or when you hold references to nodes and need to remove known nodes quickly (but JS seldom needs linked lists in typical app code).

